From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000002 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Date: Thu, 20 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] CVE-2022-0563 false positive documentation for util-linux 2.38.1-5+b1

---
 ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md | 79 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 79 insertions(+)
 create mode 100644 ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md

diff --git a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..aabbcc002
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,79 @@
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Why CVE-2022-0563 Is a False Positive for **util-linux 2.38.1-5+b1** on Debian Bookworm
+
+## Overview: What Is **util-linux**?
+
+**util-linux** is a standard Linux utility package that provides essential system tools. It includes utilities like `mount`, `umount`, `fdisk`, `lsblk`, `kill`, `login`, and others. It provides low-level functionality for disk management, process handling, terminal control, and system administration.
+
+The **util-linux** package consists of:
+- **Disk Utilities**: `fdisk`, `lsblk`, `blkid`, `mount`, `umount`
+- **System Utilities**: `kill`, `login`, `su`, `runuser`, `nsenter`
+- **Terminal Utilities**: `agetty`, `setterm`, `script`, `wall`
+- **Miscellaneous Tools**: `cal`, `dmesg`, `lscpu`, `findmnt`
+
+**util-linux** is a core system package present in virtually all Linux distributions.
+
+## Why This Vulnerability Doesn't Affect 2.38.1-5+b1
+
+Security scanning tools like **Trivy**, **Grype**, and others may flag CVE-2022-0563 on `util-linux` even when:
+
+- The CVE fix was **merged upstream on 2022-02-10** (commit `faa5a3a83ad0cb5e2c303edbfd8cd823c9d94c17`) in **util-linux v2.37.4**
+- **util-linux v2.38.1** was released on **2022-08-04** — **6 months after** the fix was merged
+- The **vulnerable readline code was completely removed** from the source before v2.38.1 was ever tagged
+- Debian additionally builds util-linux with **`--disable-chfn-chsh`**, so `chfn` and `chsh` are not compiled from this package at all
+- The `chfn` and `chsh` utilities on Debian are provided by **`src:shadow`**, a separate package unrelated to this CVE
+- The Debian Security Tracker marks this as **urgency: unimportant** with no DSA issued
+
+These factors cause scanners to **misidentify this CVE as present**, leading to **false positives** for Debian Bookworm.
+
+---
+## 📌 CVE-2022-0563 – False Positive in util-linux 2.38.1-5+b1
+
+**Component:** `chfn` and `chsh` utilities in `util-linux` when compiled with **libreadline** support
+**Issue:** The readline library uses the `INPUTRC` environment variable to load a config file. When it cannot parse the file, it prints error messages containing file content. Since readline does not use `secure_getenv()`, an unprivileged user can exploit SUID binaries (`chfn`/`chsh`) to read root-owned files.
+**Impact:** Potential partial disclosure of arbitrary files on affected versions (< 2.37.4) compiled with readline
+
+---
+
+## 🔍 Vulnerability Overview
+
+- **Component impacted:** `login-utils/chfn.c` and `login-utils/chsh.c` in util-linux with libreadline
+- **Nature of issue:** readline reads `INPUTRC` env variable without sanitization in SUID binaries, leaking file contents via error messages
+- **Severity:** Low (CVSS 3.1: 5.5)
+- **Attack vector:** Local — requires unprivileged user to set `INPUTRC` to a root-owned file path before invoking a SUID binary
+
+---
+
+## ✅ util-linux 2.38.1-5+b1 – Why This is a False Positive
+
+- **Upstream fix was merged 2022-02-10** — commit `faa5a3a83ad0cb5e2c303edbfd8cd823c9d94c17` removed readline support entirely from `chfn` and `chsh`
+- **util-linux 2.38.1 was released 2022-08-04** — 6 months after the fix; the vulnerable readline code **does not exist in the 2.38.1 source tree**
+- **Debian builds with `--disable-chfn-chsh`** — even if code were present, these utilities are never compiled from this package
+- **`chfn`/`chsh` on Debian are from `src:shadow`** — a completely different package not affected by this CVE
+- Debian Security Tracker urgency is explicitly **"unimportant"** and no DSA has been issued
+- **Scanner false positive** — triggered by generic version-range matching (`< 2.37.4`) without validating that the vulnerable code path no longer exists in 2.38.1
+
+---
+
+## ⚠️ Why You Don't Need to Fix It
+
+- **No vulnerable code present in 2.38.1** — readline removed from chfn/chsh upstream 6 months before this version was released
+- **No SUID binaries from util-linux** — `chfn`/`chsh` are provided by `shadow` on Debian, not this package
+- **Double mitigation** — source-level fix AND `--disable-chfn-chsh` build flag both independently eliminate the attack surface
+- **No security impact** on Debian Bookworm systems
+- **False positive from scanners** due to imprecise CVE version-range matching on the `util-linux` package name without code-level or build-flag validation
+
+---
+
+## 🔗 References
+
+- [**NVD Entry – CVE-2022-0563**](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2022-0563)
+- [**Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2022-0563**](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2022-0563)
+- [**Debian util-linux 2.38.1 (bookworm)**](https://packages.debian.org/bookworm/util-linux)
+- [**Upstream fix commit – faa5a3a**](https://github.com/util-linux/util-linux/commit/faa5a3a83ad0cb5e2c303edbfd8cd823c9d94c17)
+- [**Red Hat Bugzilla – CVE-2022-0563**](https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=2053151)
+- [**util-linux v2.37.4 Release Announcement**](https://lkml.org/lkml/2022/2/14/1123)
+
+---
+
